<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bruchet; Bull. mens. Soc. linn. Lyon 39 (6 (Suppl.)): 127" authorityYear="1970" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma subconcolor" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="subconcolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma subconcolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a truly arctic-alpine species with nine records from low and high arctic areas in Greenland. It was recently reported from two collections from alpine North America (Colorado, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" author="Cripps, C" journalOrPublisher="MycoKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 54" refId="B9" refString="Cripps, C, Eberhardt, U, Schuetz, N, Beker, HJ, Evenson, VS, Horak, E, 2019. The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone. MycoKeys 46: 1 - 54, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" title="The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" volume="46" year="2019">Cripps et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
), but the records here are the first from arctic North America. Described from the European Alps by Bruchet 50 years ago, it is still only known from few other locations and it must be considered a rather rare species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Habitat and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Nine collections of 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. subconcolor" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="subconcolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. subconcolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are verified, but only sparse info is given on hosts and ecology. 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix glauca" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. herbacea" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="herbacea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. herbacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Eudicots" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Bistorta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Bistorta vivipara" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="vivipara">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Bistorta vivipara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are mentioned as possible hosts. Most localities are on acid soil in agreement with the conclusion of 
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, who, in Europe, had 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. herbacea" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="herbacea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. herbacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
listed as possible host for each cited collection of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
